      <h1 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:clamp(2rem,5vw,3.25rem);font-weight:400;color:#f0ece4;line-height:1.12;letter-spacing:-0.02em;margin-bottom:1.5rem;">
        The Queensland Contract of Sale: Key Clauses Every Seller Should Understand
      </h1>
      <p style="font-size:1rem;color:rgba(240,236,228,0.6);line-height:1.8;max-width:54ch;">
        The REIQ contract is the legal foundation of every Queensland property transaction. Knowing which clauses carry real risk for sellers helps you move through the process with confidence.
      </p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- Body -->
  <div style="padding:3rem 0 7rem;">
    <div class="max-w-[780px] mx-auto px-8" style="font-size:0.97rem;color:var(--color-text-secondary);line-height:1.9;display:flex;flex-direction:column;gap:1.75rem;">

      <p>When a buyer makes an offer on your property and you accept it, that agreement is formalised in a contract of sale. In Queensland, the standard form used for residential sales is the REIQ (Real Estate Institute of Queensland) contract, which is jointly approved by the Queensland Law Society. It is a comprehensive legal document, and while your solicitor will review it in detail, sellers who understand the key clauses are better positioned to make sound decisions throughout the sale process.</p>

      <p>This article is not legal advice. It is an overview of the clauses that most often affect sellers in practice, so you know what questions to ask and what to watch for before you sign. Always have your solicitor review any contract before execution.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">What the REIQ contract is and why it is used</h2>
      <p>The REIQ standard residential contract has been the foundation of Queensland property transactions for decades. It is used because it provides a balanced, legally tested framework that both buyers and sellers, and their respective solicitors and conveyancers, understand. Deviation from the standard form is possible through special conditions, but the baseline terms are well-established and familiar to all parties in a Queensland transaction.</p>

      <p>The contract is a binding legal agreement. Once both parties have signed and any cooling-off period has elapsed, both buyer and seller are committed to the terms. Understanding what you are agreeing to before you sign is therefore essential, not optional.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Settlement date</h2>
      <p>The settlement date is when ownership of the property transfers from you to the buyer, when the balance of the purchase price is paid, and when you must vacate the property. In Queensland residential transactions, settlement periods of 30 to 90 days are most common, with 30 to 45 days being typical for transactions without significant conditions.</p>

      <p>The settlement date matters to sellers for two reasons: it determines when you receive your funds and when you need to be out. If you are purchasing another property simultaneously, the settlement date on your sale needs to be coordinated with the settlement date on your purchase to avoid bridging finance. Discuss timing requirements with your solicitor early so they can negotiate a settlement period that works for your specific circumstances.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Deposit amount and timing</h2>
      <p>The deposit is the amount the buyer pays at the time of signing or within a specified number of days after signing to confirm their commitment to the purchase. In Queensland, deposits are typically between 5% and 10% of the purchase price, though this is negotiable. The deposit is held in a trust account, usually by the real estate agent, until settlement.</p>

      <p>As a seller, you cannot access deposit funds held in trust before settlement without the buyer's written consent. The deposit is not yours until settlement is complete. If the buyer defaults, you may be entitled to retain the deposit as liquidated damages, subject to your solicitor's advice, but this is not automatic and depends on the specific circumstances of the default.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">The finance condition</h2>
      <p>A finance condition (often described as the contract being "subject to finance") allows the buyer to withdraw from the contract without penalty if they are unable to obtain finance approval within the specified period. This is the clause that most often causes sales to fall over after contracts are exchanged.</p>

      <p>From a seller's perspective, a finance condition creates a period of uncertainty during which the property is effectively off the market. Other interested buyers will typically not submit offers on a property that is already under contract, so if the finance condition is not satisfied and the buyer withdraws, you may need to restart your campaign with some market momentum lost. Understanding this risk is important when evaluating offers: an unconditional offer from a well-qualified buyer is often worth more in practice than a higher conditional offer, even if the headline price is lower.</p>

      <p>Finance condition periods in Queensland are typically 14 to 21 days, though longer periods are sometimes requested. Your solicitor can advise on what is reasonable and how to protect your interests if the period is extended.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">The building and pest condition</h2>
      <p>A building and pest condition gives the buyer the right to commission inspections of the property and to withdraw from the contract (or negotiate on price) if those inspections reveal significant issues. In Queensland, building and pest inspections are standard in most residential transactions.</p>

      <p>For sellers, a building and pest condition introduces a second window of vulnerability after the finance condition. A buyer who discovers unexpected structural issues, termite activity, or significant maintenance problems through an inspection will typically seek to renegotiate the price, request that rectification works be completed before settlement, or withdraw from the contract entirely.</p>

      <p>The best way to manage building and pest risk as a seller is to commission your own pre-sale inspections before you go to market, disclose any known issues upfront, and price the property accordingly. Buyers who discover problems through their own inspection during a campaign tend to use those findings as negotiating leverage. Buyers who are told upfront about known issues and see a price that reflects them are more likely to proceed without drama.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Special conditions and how buyers use them</h2>
      <p>Special conditions are clauses added to the standard REIQ contract by either party to address specific circumstances. Common buyer-initiated special conditions include requirements for early access to the property, conditions requiring the completion of specific repairs before settlement, subject-to-sale provisions that tie the purchase to the buyer selling their existing property, and early possession arrangements.</p>

      <p>Sellers should review all special conditions carefully before signing and consider whether each condition is genuinely necessary and whether it creates unacceptable risk or inconvenience. A condition requiring you to complete specific repairs introduces scope risk if costs escalate. A subject-to-sale condition effectively puts your settlement timeline in the hands of another party's sale campaign. Your solicitor can advise on what special conditions are reasonable, which are unusual, and how each affects your position.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">What 'time is of the essence' means</h2>
      <p>In property contracts, time is of the essence means that the dates specified are strict legal deadlines, not approximations. If a party fails to meet a time-of-the-essence obligation, the other party may be entitled to terminate the contract and claim damages. Settlement dates are typically treated as time-of-the-essence deadlines in Queensland property contracts.</p>

      <p>This matters practically because if a buyer is unable to settle on the agreed date, they are in default. As a seller, you are not automatically required to accept a request for an extension. Your solicitor can advise on what remedies are available to you if a buyer cannot settle on the agreed date, which typically includes issuing a notice to complete and potentially pursuing the deposit and damages.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">What happens if the buyer defaults before settlement</h2>
      <p>If a buyer defaults before settlement, by failing to satisfy conditions, failing to pay the deposit, or failing to settle on the agreed date, your solicitor will advise you on your options. In most cases, the first step is issuing a formal notice and allowing a specified period for the buyer to remedy the default. If the default is not remedied, you may be entitled to terminate the contract and retain the deposit.</p>

      <p>Buyer default is not common in Queensland residential transactions, but it does occur, particularly in falling markets where a buyer may find that the property they contracted to purchase is worth less by settlement than the price they agreed to pay. Understanding that this scenario exists and knowing what your protections are is part of being a prepared seller.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Why your solicitor should review the contract before you sign</h2>
      <p>The REIQ standard form provides a sound baseline, but every contract is modified by the specific terms agreed between buyer and seller, the special conditions attached, and the particular circumstances of the property and parties involved. Your solicitor will review the contract for issues specific to your property title, identify any conditions that create unusual risk, advise on the implications of the settlement timeline, and ensure that your interests are protected if something goes wrong between exchange and settlement.</p>

      <p>The cost of having a solicitor review a contract before signing is modest relative to the value of the transaction and the cost of problems that might have been identified and avoided at that stage. Do not sign a contract and then send it to your solicitor. Engage your solicitor early in the campaign so they are ready to review and respond quickly when an offer arrives.</p>

